= Introduction <sec:introduction>

Large language models are commonly evaluated by asking whether they solve tasks, follow
instructions, or provide useful answers. This thesis takes a complementary perspective. It asks
whether the form of a model's language is shaped by the form of the language that precedes it.
In particular, I study syntactic long-term alignment: the tendency of a system to reuse,
avoid, or gradually drift toward syntactic patterns that appeared earlier in a dialogue.

The phenomenon is familiar from human conversation. Speakers often converge on similar
lexical choices, comparable referring expressions, and parallel syntactic frames. Such alignment
is rarely perfect copying. It is better understood as a pressure on the distribution of choices
available to a speaker. If one participant repeatedly uses a relative clause or a passive
construction, the other participant may become slightly more likely to use the same kind of
construction later.

For language models, this question is both practical and theoretical. It is practical because many
applications place models in long conversations, tutoring sessions, editing workflows, or
interactive coding environments. In those settings, syntactic drift can change the perceived
style of the assistant. It is theoretical because alignment effects give us a way to ask how much
of a model's behavior is driven by abstract task instructions and how much is driven by the
surface form of the prompt. This distinction echoes broader debates about form, meaning, and
understanding in neural language systems #cite("bender-koller-2020-climbing").


The rest of the thesis is organized as follows. Chapter 2 reviews syntactic alignment in human
dialogue and summarizes related work on formal syntax and model evaluation. Chapter 3
introduces the datasets and the annotation pipeline. Chapter 4 presents the main alignment
experiments. Chapter 5 discusses qualitative patterns, limitations, and implications for prompt
design.

= Background

The study of alignment begins with the observation that dialogue is coordinated at many
levels. Participants coordinate topics, turn boundaries, referring expressions, lexical choices,
and grammatical forms. This coordination reduces effort: once a construction has been used, it
becomes easier for both speakers to reuse it. Psycholinguistic work often explains this with
priming, shared representations, or interactive alignment mechanisms.

In computational settings, alignment is harder to define. A language model has no stable
communicative intention in the human sense. It samples or selects continuations from a
distribution conditioned on context. Nevertheless, the output distribution can reflect structural
properties of earlier text. If a prompt contains many subordinate clauses, later responses may
become more likely to contain subordinate clauses as well.

The difficulty is that surface similarity can be misleading. Two responses may both contain
long sentences without sharing a syntactic construction. Conversely, two responses can differ
lexically while sharing an abstract dependency pattern. For this reason, the experiments in this
thesis use parsed representations rather than raw string overlap.

== Related Work

Syntactic priming has been studied extensively in human production. Classic experiments show
that speakers are more likely to reuse a syntactic frame after hearing or producing it. The effect
has been observed in dialogue, picture description, and sentence completion tasks. It is usually
small but reliable, and it interacts with lexical repetition, semantic similarity, and discourse
context.

Work on neural language models has focused more often on semantic consistency,
instruction-following, and factuality. However, several strands of research are relevant here.
Prompt sensitivity studies show that small changes in wording can change model behavior.
Style transfer and persona consistency studies show that models can preserve surface features
across a generation. Long-context evaluations show that models can retrieve and reuse details
from earlier passages.

The analysis also draws on formal accounts of grammar. Combinatory Categorial Grammar is
one example of a framework in which lexical entries and combinatory rules jointly determine
the space of possible derivations #cite("kuhlmann-etal-2015-lexicalization"). The experiments
below do not implement a CCG parser, but the general point is important: syntactic form is not
merely a string-level property. It involves structured dependencies that must be approximated
carefully when measured automatically.

