= Data and Methods

The experiments use synthetic conversations designed to isolate syntactic form from semantic
content. Each conversation consists of a neutral task description, a context paragraph, and a
probe question. The context paragraph appears in one of two variants. The variants express the
same content but differ in the target construction. The probe question then asks for a response
that is semantically compatible with both variants.

This design makes it possible to compare responses across matched pairs. If the model sees the
passive-heavy variant, does it produce more passive clauses in the answer than when it sees the
active-heavy variant? If it sees a context with many relative clauses, does it produce more
relative clauses in a later explanation?

== Prompt Construction

Prompts were written in pairs. Each pair has a high-alignment condition and a low-alignment
condition. The high-alignment condition contains repeated instances of the target construction.
The low-alignment condition uses alternative constructions with the same propositional
content. The probe is identical across the pair.

For example, a passive condition might describe several observations as "the file was checked",
"the result was recorded", and "the summary was revised". The matched active condition would
use "the assistant checked the file", "the script recorded the result", and "the student revised
the summary". The final probe asks for an explanation of the procedure without mentioning
voice.

#figure(caption: [Schematic contrast between matched prompt variants.])[
  #sample-figure(
    [Variant A: active frames | Variant B: passive frames],
    [Both variants describe the same sequence of events. Only syntactic realization is changed.]
  )
] <fig:variants>

The prompts were also balanced for length. Exact equality is impossible because constructions
have different word counts, but the average difference between paired contexts was kept below
five percent. Pairs with larger differences were revised or removed.

== Target Constructions

The analysis focuses on four construction families: active-passive alternations, relative
clauses, complement clauses, and prepositional phrase sequences. These constructions were
chosen because they are common enough to appear naturally in generated text but structured
enough to be detected by a parser.

