= Results

The results show consistent but construction-dependent alignment. Passive voice and relative
clauses produce the clearest effects. Complement clauses show a smaller effect, and
prepositional phrase sequences are noisy. These differences are consistent with the intuition
that some constructions are easier for the model to track and reproduce than others.

== Main Alignment Effects

The largest effect appears for passive voice. In passive-rich contexts, the model produces more
passive clauses in the probe response than in matched active contexts. The difference is not
large in absolute terms, but it is stable across prompt families.

Relative clauses show a similar pattern. Contexts with repeated relative clauses increase the
rate of relative clauses in later responses. Qualitative inspection suggests that the model often
uses relative clauses to maintain the explanatory style of the context.

#figure(kind: table, caption: [Estimated alignment effects by construction family.])[
  #table(
    columns: (1.6fr, 1.2fr, 1.4fr, 1.4fr),
    inset: 6pt,
    table.header([Construction], [Effect], [95% CI], [Interpretation]),
    [Passive voice], [+3.8 pp], [[+2.1, +5.4]], [Clear],
    [Relative clauses], [+2.9 pp], [[+1.0, +4.6]], [Clear],
    [Complement clauses], [+1.2 pp], [[-0.1, +2.5]], [Weak],
    [PP sequences], [+0.6 pp], [[-1.4, +2.2]], [Unclear],
  )
] <tab:effects>

The table is intentionally modest. The important point is not that the model becomes a mirror
of the prompt. Rather, the distribution shifts. In an interactive setting, such shifts can
accumulate across turns and contribute to the perceived style of the system.

== Persistence Across Turns

Alignment decays with distance, but it does not vanish immediately. When one filler turn is
inserted between the context and the probe, the passive effect remains visible. With three filler
turns, the effect becomes smaller and less reliable. Relative clauses show a similar but slightly
faster decay.

This pattern suggests that syntactic information is retained as part of the recent dialogue
state. It is not merely a token-local continuation effect. At the same time, the decay indicates
that syntax competes with newer content and instructions.

